      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI < 5% for hemolysis index QoI on production mesh.",
      "rationale": "Three-mesh GCI study at the nominal operating point yields GCI = 2.3% for the hemolysis index, satisfying the < 5% criterion. The 9.8 M cell mesh is adopted for all five COU operating points. Discretization error is assumed comparable across operating points given similar flow topology; no separate GCI study was conducted at off-nominal conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) match CFD boundary conditions within ±3%.",
      "rationale": "PIV and hemolysis bench experiments were conducted with phosphate-buffered saline (viscosity 0.00089 Pa·s at 37°C) matching CFD fluid properties within 1.5%. Inlet flow rate was controlled to ±1.2% and rotational speed to ±0.5%. Boundary condition fidelity is confirmed at the nominal validation point."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "NIH relative error ≤ 15% at the validation operating point.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH at the nominal operating point differs from measured mean by 8.5%, within the 15% acceptance band. Comparison metric is the normalised index of hemolysis consistent with ASTM F1841. Output comparison is limited to the nominal operating condition; the acceptance criterion does not address whether the 15% tolerance holds across the full COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to the clinical acceptance criterion RH < 1.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate is the primary decision QoI and directly supports the regulatory acceptance criterion. Hemolysis index is computed via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model, which integrates scalar stress exposure along Lagrangian pathlines under the assumption of linear additivity. This assumption is stated explicitly in the model documentation and is the theoretical precondition underpinning the entire hemolysis accumulation calculation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry and fluid are representative of the COU pump and blood analogue; at least one operating condition overlaps the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (identical to the COU device) and a blood analogue fluid. The nominal operating point (3.5 L/min, 2500 RPM) lies within the COU operating envelope of five flow-speed combinations. Relevance is therefore judged adequate at MRL 2. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger model's theoretical precondition — that stress accumulation is linear and additive — was satisfied at the single validated point; no assessment was performed to confirm it holds at the four remaining COU points, particularly at the high-speed condition (3.5 L/min, 3500 RPM) where shear stress magnitudes may exceed the empirical correlation range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; commercial solver vendor documentation is sufficient.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2 with medium model influence, independent assessment of numerical solver error beyond vendor documentation is not required. This factor is scoped to not-assessed status consistent with ASME V&V 40 Table 4 guidance."
    },
    {
